### Dual-Engine Rule (critical for task mode annotations)

| What you're building | Mode annotation | Language |
|---------------------|-----------------|----------|
| `bl/` engine code | `[mode:python]` | Python |
| `masonry/mcp_server/` tools | `[mode:python]` | Python |
| `masonry/src/schemas/` | `[mode:python]` | Python |
| `masonry/src/routing/` | `[mode:python]` | Python |
| `masonry/src/hooks/*.js` | no annotation (default developer) | JS |
| `masonry/src/engine/*.js` | no annotation (default developer) | JS |
| `masonry/src/engine/cli/*.js` | no annotation (default developer) | JS |
| Frontend / Kiln Electron | `[mode:typescript]` | TypeScript |
| Docker / infra | `[mode:devops]` | — |
| Schema design / migrations | `[mode:database]` | — |
| Security audit | `[mode:security]` | — |

**Rule**: Hot-path work (hooks, routing, JS engine) stays JS. Campaign/ML/tmux/Recall work stays Python. Never cross the engine boundary in a single task.

